TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effects of Repeat Collaboration on Creative Abrasion
AU  - Skilton, Paul F.
AU  - Dooley, Kevin J.
Y1  - 2010/01/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.35.1.zok118
DO  - 10.5465/amr.35.1.zok118
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 118
EP  - 134
VL  - 35
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Building on research that suggests a negative relationship between repeat collaboration and team creativity, we propose that team mental models developed in earlier projects are likely to interfere with the processes that constitute creative abrasion: idea generation, disclosure/advocacy, and convergence. Suppression of these processes leads to less creative outcomes. We conclude by proposing that these negative effects can be mitigated by process and project charter interventions and by outsider entry into the project team.
AB  - Building on research that suggests a negative relationship between repeat collaboration and team creativity, we propose that team mental models developed in earlier projects are likely to interfere with the processes that constitute creative abrasion: idea generation, disclosure/advocacy, and convergence. Suppression of these processes leads to less creative outcomes. We conclude by proposing that these negative effects can be mitigated by process and project charter interventions and by outsider entry into the project team.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.35.1.zok118
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.35.1.zok118
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Cross-Understanding: Implications for Group Cognition and Performance
AU  - Huber, George P.
AU  - Lewis, Kyle
Y1  - 2010/01/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.35.1.zok6
DO  - 10.5465/amr.35.1.zok6
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 6
EP  - 26
VL  - 35
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this paper we articulate the cross-understanding construct, a group-level compositional construct having as its components each group member's understanding of each other member's mental model. We describe how the cross-understanding construct explains particular inconsistencies in the groups literature, how it provides explanations for specific group outcomes and processes beyond the explanations currently in the literature, and how different levels and different distributions of cross-understanding affect group performance and learning.
AB  - In this paper we articulate the cross-understanding construct, a group-level compositional construct having as its components each group member's understanding of each other member's mental model. We describe how the cross-understanding construct explains particular inconsistencies in the groups literature, how it provides explanations for specific group outcomes and processes beyond the explanations currently in the literature, and how different levels and different distributions of cross-understanding affect group performance and learning.
